### Garbage Collection and Memory Optimization

Node.js uses V8's generational garbage collection with Scavenger (young generation) and Mark-Sweep-Compact (old generation). Frequent GC pauses cause latency spikes, particularly problematic in latency-sensitive applications. GC behavior depends on allocation rate, object lifetimes, and heap size configuration.

Monitor GC using the --trace-gc flag or diagnostic channels. Use NODE_OPTIONS='--max-old-space-size=4096' to increase heap size, but larger heaps mean longer GC pauses. Profile memory with heap snapshots. Optimize by reducing allocations, using object pools for frequently-created short-lived objects, and streaming large data.

```typescript
import { performance, PerformanceObserver } from 'perf_hooks';

const obs = new PerformanceObserver((list) => {
  list.getEntries().forEach((entry) => {
    if (entry.entryType === 'gc') {
      console.log(`GC: ${entry.duration}ms (type: ${entry.detail.kind})`);
    }
  });
});

obs.observe({ entryTypes: ['gc'], buffered: true });

// Run with: node --expose-gc app.js
for (let i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {
  const obj = { data: Buffer.alloc(1024) };
}
```


**Common interview trap:** Increasing heap size doesn't always improve performance; it lengthens GC pauses. The optimal size depends on workload. Also, many developers don't realize that full GC (Mark-Sweep-Compact) is much slower than Scavenger.

