### async_hooks Resource Lifecycle: destroy Timing and Context Leak Detection

The `async_hooks` `destroy` callback fires when the async resource is garbage collected — not when the operation completes. For Promises, `destroy` may fire long after resolution if the Promise object is still referenced. For Timers, it fires after the callback runs and the timer is freed.

This timing difference is critical for leak detection: if `init` is called more frequently than `destroy`, async resources are accumulating. This is the basis for tools like `async-resource-tracker`.

```typescript
import { createHook } from 'async_hooks';

const asyncResources = new Map<number, { type: string; timestamp: number; stack: string }>();

const hook = createHook({
  init(asyncId, type, triggerAsyncId) {
    if (type === 'PROMISE' || type === 'Timeout') {
      asyncResources.set(asyncId, {
        type,
        timestamp: Date.now(),
        stack: new Error().stack ?? '', // capture creation site
      });
    }
  },
  destroy(asyncId) {
    asyncResources.delete(asyncId);
  },
});

hook.enable();

// Leak detector: find async resources older than 30 seconds
setInterval(() => {
  const now = Date.now();
  for (const [id, info] of asyncResources) {
    if (now - info.timestamp > 30_000) {
      console.warn(`Potential async resource leak: type=${info.type}, age=${now - info.timestamp}ms`);
      console.warn(info.stack);
    }
  }
}, 10_000);

// IMPORTANT: disable hook when not needed — it adds overhead to ALL async operations
// hook.disable();
```

**Common interview trap:** Enabling `async_hooks` with `init` for every resource type in production, expecting it to be low overhead. Capturing stack traces inside `init` (as done in many "easy" tracing examples) is extremely expensive — `new Error().stack` triggers V8's stack trace API for every Promise creation. Enable selectively by type, and never in production hot paths without benchmarking.

