### Node.js Container Memory: Heap Sizing Formula and OOM Killer Behaviour

The Linux OOM killer terminates processes when the system runs out of memory. In containers, the kernel enforces cgroup memory limits via the same OOM mechanism. Node.js V8 heap is only one component of total process memory — the OOM killer uses RSS (resident set size), which includes:

- V8 old generation (controlled by `--max-old-space-size`)
- V8 young generation (~32-64MB, not affected by `--max-old-space-size`)
- Native heap (libssl TLS buffers, libuv buffers, native addons)
- Code space (compiled JS machine code, ~10-50MB)
- OS page cache used by the process

```typescript
// Monitoring actual memory footprint
function logMemory() {
  const mem = process.memoryUsage();
  console.log({
    // V8 heap — controlled by --max-old-space-size
    heapUsed: `${(mem.heapUsed / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,
    heapTotal: `${(mem.heapTotal / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,
    // Total process memory — what OOM killer measures
    rss: `${(mem.rss / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,
    // Native buffers allocated outside V8 heap (Buffer.alloc)
    external: `${(mem.external / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,
    // ArrayBuffer memory
    arrayBuffers: `${(mem.arrayBuffers / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,
  });
}

// Safe heap size calculation:
// rss = old-space + young-space (~50MB) + native (~30-100MB) + code (~20MB)
// --max-old-space-size = containerLimit * 0.75 - 100  (approximate)

// For 512MB container:
// --max-old-space-size = 512 * 0.75 - 100 = 284  → use 256MB (round down)

// K8s: always set requests = limits to prevent OOM from memory overcommit
// Never use only "requests" without "limits" for Node.js processes
```

**Common interview trap:** Confusing `heapUsed` with `rss` and sizing the container based on typical `heapUsed` values. Under load, `rss` is typically 1.5-3× `heapUsed` due to young gen, fragmentation, and native allocations. A Node.js process with 200MB `heapUsed` may have 400MB `rss`. Container limit must be set relative to `rss`, not `heapUsed`.

